just put up with that, I guess. Oh, sure, yeah. I'm well used to that. Yeah, I'm
sure. Tell me your front name again. Daryl. Daryl. Yeah, Daryl. Okay. I'm an

00:18.460 --> 00:28.400
English teacher here at Odessa College. Right. Okay, listen, you obviously had
an extremely varied background, and I wondered if you could just say a few words

00:28.400 --> 00:43.300
about how you began as a writer. Okay. I began to write when I was an able
seaman in the Merchant Marine, and how that came about was that I left home

00:43.300 --> 00:52.140
before I graduated from high school. It's a fascinating thing. I lecture at
colleges and universities all over the United States and in England and in

00:52.140 --> 01:03.300
France, And I have yet to get my high school diploma. Someday somebody will
grant me an honorary high school diploma. But anyway, I was on the ship. And you

01:03.300 --> 01:12.480
had a lot of time to read. And I conceived the idea of an absolutely foolproof
crime that would net me thousands and thousands of dollars. And I even did

01:12.480 --> 01:23.660
research on it. I was on a coastwise tanker. And as I was going up and down the
coast, when we stopped at a port, I would send off a letter to the railroad, so

01:23.660 --> 01:29.360
it was one of the things that was involved, and the insurance companies, that
was another, and the post office, that was still another. I got all my research

01:29.360 --> 01:41.780
done as to how to commit this particular kind of robbery, and they had letters
carefully written so that nobody would know what I was up to. And when I had all

01:41.780 --> 01:55.320
my material, I found that I did not have the immoral courage to commit the
crime, so I wrote it as a story. this was way back in the late 30s and i sent my

01:55.320 --> 02:04.600
story off to a newspaper syndicate i didn't know anything about writing
particularly and there was they were buying a 1500 word short short stories that

02:04.600 --> 02:15.160
they published every day in the in the syndicate and uh when i got up to new
york in the ship to my amazement i got a letter of acceptance and uh so i quit

02:15.160 --> 02:28.040
the sea and and came ashore to be a writer. And I got my money, not on
acceptance, but on publication. And it was five whole dollars. And they would

02:28.040 --> 02:37.340
buy one and sometimes two stories a week, but no more. And so four and a half
months or so, I lived on five and sometimes ten dollars a week. My room cost me

02:37.340 --> 02:51.780
seven. And whatever I saved, I could eat. And I learned a lot about being
hungry. Did you ever notice that pound cake has no crust on the ends? What they

02:51.780 --> 03:00.700
do is chop them off and they sell them in their day-old store. And at that time,
you could get a whole shopping bag full of cake ends for a nickel. And so I used

03:00.700 --> 03:08.600
to live on that. One time, I got a whole shopping bag full and it was moldy, but
I ate it anyhow. And I was so sick, I didn't eat for three days, and so I saved

03:08.600 --> 03:23.040
myself some money. You know, like that. It was a hard school. it really was but
then I finally after some months of that and I think I went back to C for a

03:23.040 --> 03:37.940
short while I finally met John Campbell in 1939 early 1939 he was the editor of
Astounding Science Fiction and a wonderful fantasy magazine called Unknown and

03:39.060 --> 03:47.680
so I started writing for him and then after that it just exploded One time I had
four stories on the stands at the same time, and those two magazines I had to

03:47.680 --> 03:49.760
get two new names.

03:51.880 --> 03:54.220
So it was an interesting beginning.

03:57.060 --> 04:06.020
Okay, excellent. Now you've done a lot of writing for the pulps, but I don't
think anybody would categorize you as a pulp writer. Well, you know, this is

04:06.020 --> 04:18.040
difficult with the whole matter of categorization anyway. We're in the grip of
the taxonomist and people who put labels on things and stick them into cubby

04:18.040 --> 04:28.320
holes. Taxonomy has its uses, there's no question about that. You have to be
able to find and retrieve information and that's what taxonomy is all about. But

04:28.320 --> 04:37.860
more and more, there seems to come over our whole culture the idea that if you
can put a label on it, you understand it. And that is not what taxonomy is for.

04:37.860 --> 04:49.020
Taxonomy is handles by which you can pick something up and look at it, but for
so many people in so many ways, the label is sufficient. You know, he's a

04:49.020 --> 04:50.740
Republican, or his mother was a Jew,

04:54.140 --> 05:04.960
you know, he's a poet, he's in ESPIT, or whatever. They're all labels, and just
so little effort made to understand what's under these labels. Pulp fiction has

05:04.960 --> 05:13.580
suffered from the same thing. Pulp actually referred to the kind of paper it was
printed on, not to its quality. There was the pulps, and there were the slicks.

05:13.720 --> 05:22.820
The slicks were magazines like the Sidered Evening Post and Collier's. And
Ladies' Home Journal. And pulps were things like Black Mask and Air War Stories

05:22.820 --> 05:32.440
and science fiction and fantasy and the like. But it's so easy for the
taxonomists and for people who don't pay proper attention to what was going on

05:32.440 --> 05:43.540
to feel that pulp was a qualitative comment and slick was also qualitative.
Slick paper was better literature than pulp paper. Some of the finest writing

05:43.540 --> 05:52.960
around and some of the best pulp writers as such. I mean, the best writers of
the time began in pulp and they only gravitated to the slicks not because they

05:52.960 --> 06:03.160
got better, but because they got paid more. Ray Bradbury is a perfect example of
that. so is Dasha Lennon and the like

