experiment deliberately or is it something that comes naturally to you? It's

09:15.580 --> 09:26.460
absolutely deliberate. The creation of a style, you can go a long way in the
literary business. Steinbeck did it, Aldous Huxley did it. One of the stunning

09:26.460 --> 09:38.340
examples is Ray Bradbury. but you develop a style and then you stick to it,
pretty soon you become imitable. That is to say anybody with any real facility

09:38.340 --> 09:49.500
with words can sit down and write a pure paragraph of Steinbeck or for that
matter Hemingway. To imitate Hemingway and Steinbeck is very, very easy and

09:49.500 --> 10:02.000
Bradbury particularly is extremely easy to imitate. But you don't imitate Samuel
Delaney. for example. You don't imitate, I mean, not by the paragraph. I'm not

10:02.000 --> 10:11.400
saying that you can sit down and write a Bradbury story or a Hemingway story.
That's a different matter. But we're talking just about the matter of style. And

10:11.400 --> 10:22.800
yes, it's a very conscious effort on my part to be able to write with facility
in any of a number of styles. And sometimes they're first-person stories. And I

10:22.800 --> 10:31.380
write out of the mouth of the person who's talking. And not everybody talks You
know, in a high literary style That's what I thought Aldous Huxley For mostly

10:31.380 --> 10:43.080
You read an Aldous Huxley novel And Aldous Huxley talks like Aldous Huxley And
old men talk like Aldous Huxley And little girls talk like Aldous Huxley It's a

10:43.080 --> 10:54.660
Monotone All the words come out of all the mouths With the same kind of cadence
And I don't consider This really top writing Why I admire Delany so much Is

10:54.660 --> 11:05.240
that when he talks Ghetto Black, it is for real. But if he has two characters
discussing modern American poetry, they talk in terms of William Carlos Williams

11:06.440 --> 11:20.040
or T.S. Eliot. And he knows, he's got a good ear, he knows the cadence of this
kind of writing. And I admire that so very much. That you can't imitate. And so

11:20.040 --> 11:31.540
I consciously do that. Okay, James Gunn has written that because of Sturgeon,
other writers have been freer to write what they wish to write and able to find

11:31.540 --> 11:40.440
a market for it. I wondered if you were conscious of yourself as having that
kind of a role. Not at all. Not at all. I tell you, the last few years have been

11:40.440 --> 11:54.080
real revelations to me. For one thing, I didn't realize that I'd had so much
personal impact on people until, what was it, six years or so now, Now, I went

11:54.080 --> 12:02.180
to Italy, and a woman came up to me dragging an interpreter, and the interpreter
said she doesn't speak any English, but there are two things that she wants to

12:02.180 --> 12:11.700
tell you. One of them is that you write women better than any writer she knows.
And the other thing is that because of something that you wrote, she did not

12:11.700 --> 12:23.640
kill herself one night. And the woman began to cry, and the interpreter began to
cry, and I began to cry. And it was quite an experience. I suddenly realized

12:23.640 --> 12:33.060
that what I have done, apparently, I've been able to reach a great many people
far deeper than I had any idea that I was doing. When I look back over the mail

12:33.060 --> 12:43.040
that I've gotten over the years, I realize how many people in how many different
ways have told me that same kind of thing. It's extremely gratifying. It's also

12:43.040 --> 12:50.560
a little frightening. I mean, it's frightening enough to make you terrified of
touching your typewriter.

12:54.820 --> 12:55.640
what's his name

