been existed upon which writers within the field could build. It's so gratifying
to read a thing like that, you know. Years after the fact, Halsburg never told

14:21.860 --> 14:34.640
me, I think he was writing that in an essay. And I came on it quite by accident.
But apparently that was the case. And I'll tell you quickly a story. A few years

14:34.640 --> 14:44.520
ago, there was a little boy who went to see his buddy. He was six or seven years
old. His mother told him to be back before dark. And he was so busy playing with

14:44.520 --> 14:53.480
his friend that he looked out the window and saw it was dark and he went rushing
home and like little kids will he dragged a stick along a picket fence and when

14:53.480 --> 15:01.480
he got to the corner he whanged it against the lamppost and immediately all the
lights in the northeastern United States went out. Remember that one? That big

15:01.480 --> 15:11.660
blackout? He went rushing home to his mother weeping and threw himself into her
arms and said, God mommy I didn't mean it. I didn't mean it. Well this is the

15:11.660 --> 15:22.180
way I felt when I first read things like this. very gratifying and very
surprising to me no, I did not do that on purpose honest to God, mom, I didn't

15:22.180 --> 15:33.300
mean it yeah, a lot of critics that I've read feel that same way that's a pretty
universal opinion in relation to that a number of critics and authors also

15:33.300 --> 15:42.080
identify you as sort of a shatterer of taboos some of the themes that you wrote
about just hadn't been handled in science fiction before yeah, that's right,

15:42.320 --> 15:45.880
that I've done on purpose Stand by for a coffee.

15:49.500 --> 16:02.580
Coughing over. Yes, I have purposely broken taboos. And, you know, I wrote the
first stories in science fiction about homosexuality, for example, which dealt

16:02.580 --> 16:12.920
with homosexuality and with incest. And I had a three-parter in Omni last year
which dealt with cannibalism. But these stories were not about homosexuality.

16:13.760 --> 16:23.320
and about incest and about cannibalism. Essentially, they were about
confrontation. All my life, I've been infuriated by people who shuck away from

16:23.320 --> 16:31.060
an idea. I don't want to hear about that. Oh, don't tell me that. I don't want
to hear it. You know, that always angers me. Because only by confrontation can

16:31.060 --> 16:40.820
we really learn anything. The whole history of, well, a subject like
masturbation, for example, which absolutely terrified the three or four

16:40.820 --> 16:54.820
generations before mine, and preoccupied them too. The inventor of one of our
more famous breakfast foods, he was a nutritional doctor, and he used to write

16:54.820 --> 17:04.660
dietary and medical advice books for the home. And about 75% of them has to do
with masturbation and how it will make your hair fall out and give you a

17:04.660 --> 17:15.300
softening of the brain and tuberculosis and cancer and all kinds of things.
nowadays with a little confrontation and a little research and study, you can

17:15.300 --> 17:29.860
read in the highest level of women's magazines not only how to do it but how to
do it well and it's become a totally accepted practice but the horror that went

17:29.860 --> 17:39.520
on because people would not confront it or would not find out what the truth was
caused so much frightful damage I mean, people committed suicide over that. I

17:39.520 --> 17:55.640
had a relative whose whole life was absolutely made hell by his preoccupation
with that. To be tempted and finally to yield and then feel guilty and feel

17:55.640 --> 18:05.000
guilty and so guilty that he would never tell anybody about it. It wrecked his
whole life. That was a lot of years ago. I mean, it was in the past generation.

18:05.000 --> 18:16.080
but it's an example of what I mean now people have got to confront if we meet
you'll probably see me wearing a little silver medallion it's a letter cute with

18:16.080 --> 18:27.780
an arrow to it it's my trademark and what it means is ask the next question to
me it's the symbol of everything that humanity has ever created and it's the

18:27.780 --> 18:35.780
only way it has been created by people asking the next question the one that
follows and so often people ask the next question and the one that follows and

18:35.780 --> 18:42.960
the one that follows until they suddenly come to a question they don't want to
ask because they're afraid they might get the answer and there they stop and

18:42.960 --> 18:52.360
when you stop asking the next question you die, you become a zombie and join the
ranks of the zombies you see marching around you who have stopped asking the

18:52.360 --> 19:03.860
next question it's a very symbol of life and of progress and of science and
everything toward basic truth when you ever reach basic truth you'll find not a

19:03.860 --> 19:13.580
thing or a precept, but you'll find a process. You'll find something going on.
And this is the way I've been thinking apparently all my life. I get very, very

19:13.580 --> 19:23.760
irritated when I find that people refuse to think beyond a certain point.
There's a bumper sticker that goes around in the Bible Belt. God said it. I

19:23.760 --> 19:32.740
believe it. That settled it. When you see a bumper sticker like that, you've
just heard the crash of a closing mind. there's plenty of room out there to

19:32.740 --> 19:40.580
confront the whole idea of God and to go on with it and ask the next question
and the question that follows without committing any particular kind of sin

